## 2. Search Intent & Target Audience

**Who is searching this:** The audience is primarily first-time renters, recent graduates, solo professionals, and budget-conscious urban dwellers in the early-to-active research phase of the rental journey. A significant secondary cluster is location-intent searchers (PAA data confirms heavy geographic modifiers: Chicago, Los Angeles, Spokane, Colorado Springs) who are actively comparing units in specific cities.

**What problem they're solving:** They need either a foundational definition of what a studio apartment is, a cost-versus-value comparison (studio vs. one-bedroom, studio vs. roommate), or location-specific pricing to determine affordability before contacting landlords or browsing listings.

**Answer format expected:** A layered hybrid — opening with a crisp definition (featured snippet format), followed by comparison tables (cost, unit types, cities), a decision framework, and an FAQ block. Both Google's PAA data and Claude's response confirm this expectation; searchers want scannable, structured content, not long-form prose.

