### 5c. Citability Blueprint for the Writer

**Rule 1 — First-Paragraph Rule (Opening 100 Words)**
The opening paragraph must contain: (a) an explicit, standalone definition of "studio apartment" that uses the phrase "a single open room where the living area, sleeping area, and kitchen are combined, with only the bathroom separately enclosed"; (b) a specific size range in square feet ("typically 300–600 sq ft in the United States"); and (c) a direct statement of the primary use case ("the most affordable rental option for solo renters and first-time apartment seekers"). Do not bury the definition. Do not open with a question, anecdote, or history. AI engines extract the first coherent definitional statement they encounter — make it unambiguous and complete.

**Rule 2 — Structured Data Rule (Comparison Tables)**
Every major comparison in this article must be formatted as a named HTML table, not as prose. Required tables: (1) Studio vs. Alcove vs. Convertible vs. Junior 1BR — with columns for Layout, Typical Size, and Key Difference; (2) Rent by City — with columns for City, Median Rent, Affordable Neighborhoods, Expensive Neighborhoods; (3) Studio vs. One-Bedroom cost comparison — with rows for median rent, utility cost estimate, storage, privacy, and typical lease terms; (4) International names for studio apartments — country, local term, notes. Tables are the primary format AI engines use for structured citation extraction. Each table must have a descriptive heading immediately above it that includes a searchable phrase (e.g., "Studio Apartment Rent by City, 2024–2025").

**Rule 3 — Definition Rule (Key Terms)**
The following terms must each receive an explicit, bolded inline definition the first time they appear — not a parenthetical aside, but a structured sentence of the form "[Term] is [definition]." Required terms: **studio apartment**, **efficiency apartment**, **alcove studio**, **convertible studio**, **junior one-bedroom**, **bedsit**, **single room occupancy (SRO)**, **kitchenette**. The distinction between studio and SRO (studios have private bathrooms; SROs do not) must be stated explicitly, as both Wikipedia and Claude flag this as a common point of confusion. Do not assume the reader knows any of these distinctions.

**Rule 4 — Proof Point Rule (Benchmarks and Citable Claims)**
Every section that makes a cost or size claim must include at least one specific, citable data point. Acceptable formats: a numeric range ("$1,200–$1,700/month in Chicago"), a percentage ("studios typically cost 20–30% less than comparable one-bedrooms in the same building"), a threshold ("Walk Score above 85 generally justifies a premium studio rent"), or a size benchmark ("the US average studio is 500–600 sq ft, per standard market data"). Avoid vague comparatives ("studios are cheaper," "much smaller") without a figure attached. AI engines preferentially cite content that contains specific, quotable figures — these become the "statistics" engines pull into their responses.

**Rule 5 — FAQ Rule (Dedicated Block with Structured Q&A)**
The FAQ section must be formatted as individual H3 question headings followed immediately by a 2–4 sentence answer that begins with a direct response to the question (not a restatement of the question). The following questions are the highest-priority for AI citation because they correspond directly to gaps the AI engines identified and the PAA cluster confirms: (1) "What is the difference between a studio and an efficiency apartment?" (2) "What is an alcove studio apartment?" (3) "Can a couple live in a studio apartment?" (4) "How do I make a studio apartment feel bigger?" (5) "What should I look for when touring a studio apartment?" (6) "Is $10,000 enough to move into a first apartment?" (7) "Are studio apartments cheaper than living with roommates?" Each answer should be written as if it will be read in isolation — include the key context within the answer itself, not in the surrounding prose.

